snippet.textDisplay:
something fun that gets you all over is just finding a clear patch of grass and diving onto the ground. Find a new way to absorb your fall or tuck and roll each time, blast off the ground as you recover. fall forward, backwards, sideways. fall quickly, fall slowly. You'll never hit the same muscles the same way twice.



Flopping around like a fish on a memory foam bed can be surprisingly challenging too.

snippet.textDisplay: I have been doing home workouts since i was 17 years old (so almost 5 years now) and this is the kinds of information i explained to friends/family who go to the gyms and use machines and whatnot. gotta be extremely creative for everyone's home is a different environment needing a different set up/system. I only have dumbells up to 25 pounds and just from from that i can still do a deadlift of 225 pounds (and im only 140 pounds), it's all about translating home workouts (full body) to the gym/life. in my book if your workout is not practical and won't help you in real life it is called dead weight and should be substituted out. great video as always
